---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BrandMark from '../components/BrandMark.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import config from '../data/config.json';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Grubble Eats"
  description="Group food decisions take twenty minutes and end in compromise. Grubble Eats fixes that with swipe-based, AI-enhanced, group-aware decisions — real Google Places data and real Anthropic Claude, working today."
>
  <header class="px-6 py-6 border-b border-border-subtle">
    <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-3" aria-label="Grubble Eats home">
      <BrandMark variant="squircle" size={36} title="Grubble Eats" class="rounded-md" />
      <span class="font-display font-extrabold text-lg">Grubble Eats&trade;</span>
    </a>
  </header>

  <main class="px-6 py-16">
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-content">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tightest">About Grubble Eats</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-text-secondary text-pretty">
        The food decision app built for groups, not just solo discovery.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-8 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-secondary [&_h2]:text-2xl [&_h2]:font-display [&_h2]:font-extrabold [&_h2]:tracking-tightest [&_h2]:text-text-primary [&_h2]:mb-3 [&_a]:text-primary [&_a]:underline">
        <section>
          <h2>The problem</h2>
          <p>
            Deciding where to eat with friends is a small, daily, universal kind
            of misery. The group chat loops for twenty minutes, three people say
            "I'm easy," nobody actually is, and you land on the same place you
            always go — or somewhere nobody's excited about. Existing food apps
            make it worse: they're built for one person browsing a catalog alone,
            not a group trying to agree.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>The approach</h2>
          <p>
            Grubble is group-first. It's swipe-based — flick through a deck of
            real nearby spots instead of scrolling menus. It's AI-enhanced —
            Claude reasons about what the whole room will agree on and explains
            why a place won. And it's group-aware — friends join a live session
            and swipe the same stack in real time, with match rules that scale
            from solo to a table of six. The decision is the product.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>What's real today</h2>
          <p>
            This isn't a pitch deck mockup. The
            <a href={config.urls.appDemo} rel="noopener noreferrer">live demo</a>
            runs on real data: every card is an open restaurant pulled from
            Google Places, with real photos, hours, and ratings. The AI surfaces
            — card blurbs, the recommender, vibe previews, and the group
            tiebreaker — run on real Anthropic Claude. Group sessions sync
            between phones over a Cloudflare backend. Port St. Lucie alone has
            50+ spots live in the deck.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-4">
            <a href={config.urls.appDemo} rel="noopener noreferrer" class="font-bold">Try the demo at app.grubbleeats.com &rarr;</a>
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Built by Tenvaro</h2>
          <p>
            Grubble Eats is designed and built in-house by
            <a href={config.urls.parent} rel="noopener noreferrer">Tenvaro</a>
            — every screen, swipe, and AI surface shipped end to end. The
            stack is lean and modern: a Cloudflare
            backend (Workers + D1) for sessions and waitlist, Flutter for native
            and web from one codebase, and Claude powering the AI surfaces. New
            updates land weekly.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Contact &amp; press</h2>
          <p>
            For press, partnership, or investor questions, reach us at
            <a href={`mailto:${config.contact.support}`}>{config.contact.support}</a>.
            More detail for investors and recruiters lives on the
            <a href="/press">press page</a>.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-12">
        <a href="/" class="text-primary font-bold underline">&larr; Back to home</a>
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
